I wonder if we should define these classes separately. There are plenty classes that only satisfy one of them: mono, epi, finite scheme morphisms etc.

But maybe there isn't much API to develop and there isn't much gain.
Mono and epi satisfy an even more stronger condition: if the composition is mono, then the first map is. Indeed, I do not think this would be a significant gain.

I noticed that a lot of these are formalized with subset rather than le. Is there a reason to this? It will require either a lot more duplication or rewrites into le when using the order API (when considering the disjunction of properties, or monotone property constructors etc.)
(out of scope of this PR)
